{
  "texts": [
    "Although these terms are related, they are not used interchangeably; scenes are a subset of the broader remote sensing images, representing the areas of interest for scene classification.",
    "Figure 1 shows how the main object generally occupies the majority of the image in the case of a natural image, while objects in remote sensing images are often tiny and scattered, and the redundant background takes up the majority of the image as shown in Fig. 1 (c).",
    "Furthermore, not all of the information in the image is relevant to recognizing the visual scene.",
    "Vehicles and roads are particularly significant for identifying highway scenes, as illustrated in Fig. 1 (b), while houses and trees in the background deteriorate the classification decision.",
    "As a result, when focusing on the features of remote sensing images, we should pay greater attention to the most discriminative features of objects and eliminate the background interference."
  ]
}